comments.body:
btw, please try running;
euca-modify-property -p loadbalancing.loadbalancer_emi=emi-9D113D10
(using a valid EMI-id from your cloud) to get ELB "configured". Let me know if that helps with this login issue.

At this point, the user console isn't set up to work with optional features. We hope to have a better mechanism in 3.4 for determining user capabilities. So, the user needs to have access to the services the console supports, if only read-only access.

{noformat}
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Action": [
        "autoscaling:Describe*",
        "cloudwatch:Describe*",
        "cloudwatch:Get*",
        "cloudwatch:List*",
        "ec2:Describe*",
        "elasticloadbalancing:Describe*"
      ],
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}
{noformat}

I have successfully logged in when no ELB is configured. I guess the policy part is the key here. A simplified allow all policy is:

{code}
{
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Action": "*",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}
{code}

I've been able to login to the console with only this policy;
{ "Statement": [ { "Effect": "Allow", "Action": "ec2:*", "Resource": "*" } ] }

Notice, no perms for anything but ec2. Is there a more minimal policy we should work with?

This worked for 3.3.1, but I can try to do more for 3.4

Hi David,

Just curious,
if ListMetrics and DescribeAlarms are failing, how come only ec2 permission is helping with CloudWatch/Auto Scaling? Shouldn't the following policy be helpful in this case,

{noformat}
{
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Action": [
        "cloudwatch:DescribeAlarms",
        "cloudwatch:ListMetrics"
      ],
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}
{noformat}

BTW, if logged in in the machine running the console, the admin will receive wall messages from syslog:

{code}
Message from syslogd@XXXXXX at Sep  2 15:43:47 ...
 <14>received boto server error (500,InternalFailure,User does not have permission)
{code}

I don't think this error is severe enough to use the "emerg" severity.
